One way is to add the ellipsis conditionally, based on the total number of words.  
Since [`split()`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/String/split) returns an array, you can test against the array&#39;s [length property](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/length).

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    function truncateText(text) {

      text = text.trim();
      let words = text.split(&quot; &quot;);

      return words.length &gt; 10
        ? words.slice(0, 10).join(&quot; &quot;) + &quot;...&quot;
        : text;

    }

    console.log(
      truncateText(&quot;This is a sentence that is more than ten words long.&quot;)
    );

    console.log(
      truncateText(&quot;This is a shorter sentence.&quot;)
    );

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

Incidentally, jQuery is [probably](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/40329177/jquery-trim-compared-to-string-trim) not necessary since `trim()`, `split()`, `join()`, `slice()`, and `length` are all standard (plain) JavaScript.

