Sounds like what you really need is templating, rather than variable insertion. That said, you could do it explicitly variable-by-variable, which might provide extra security.

    #!/usr/bin/env bash
    #---- doc:start ----#
    # Hello $User\n
    # This is myscript.sh
    # ${red}This will be red!${eol}
    #---- doc:end   ----#

    # template replacemenmts
    red=$&#39;\e[31m&#39;
    norm=$&#39;\e[m&#39;
    eol=$&#39;\n&#39;

    # fetch and trim...
    s=$(&lt; $0)
    s=${s%%#---- doc:end   ----#*}
    s=${s##*#---- doc:start ----#}

    # do substitutions
    s=${s//\$User/$USER}
    s=${s//\${red\}/$red}
    s=${s//\${eol\}/$eol}
    s=${s//\\n/$eol}
    
    printf &#39;%s\n%s&#39; &quot;$s&quot; &quot;$norm&quot;

This avoids using `sed` or anything else which might behave differently from platform to platform. (`sed` is different between GNU, FreeBSD/MacOS and Solaris, for example.)

Just for something to think about, [here&#39;s an example](https://github.com/chvostek/shelltools/blob/master/sshswitch) of how I tend to embed documentation within bash scripts. (And yes, I use sed. :-) )

